io.github.utk003.util.math.complex

Interface ComplexNumber<CN extends ComplexNumber<CN>>

  • Type Parameters:
    CN - A subclass of ComplexNumber
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ComplexDouble, ComplexFloat

    @ScheduledForRelease(inVersion="v3.0.0")
public interface ComplexNumber<CN extends ComplexNumber<CN>>
    A generic interface for any complex number implementation.

    This interface covers most of the basic operations for complex numbers. Notable exceptions include a scaling function (ie multiplying by scalar real numbers), magnitude, and getters/setters for the complex number's real and imaginary components. These methods' signatures vary based on whether the ComplexNumber implementation is backed by floats or doubles, and, as such, these methods are left to the needs and specifications of any individual application.

    Because of the aforementioned shortcomings in this interface declaration, objects involving this interface and its implementing classes should prefer being declared as the subclass rather than as a ComplexNumber.

    The provided implementations of ComplexNumber are ComplexFloat and ComplexDouble (backed by floats and doubles, respectively).

    Since:
    3.0.0
    Version:
    June 24, 2021
    Author:
    Utkarsh Priyam (utk003)
    See Also:
    ComplexFloat, ComplexDouble

 @NotNull
CN multiply(int p,
                                                     int q)
        Multiplies this ComplexNumber by the rational number p/q.

        If p = q = 0, it is equivalent to multiplying the complex number by 1. In other words, if p = q = 0, the complex number this object represents does not change.

        Parameters:

        q - The denominator of the rational number to multiply by
        Returns:
        This ComplexNumber, after the multiplication
        Throws:

      • normalize

        @Contract(value="-> this")
 @NotNull
CN normalize()
        Normalizes this complex number.

        This method scales down this complex number's real and imaginary components by its magnitude. When this process finishes, the resulting number's magnitude will be exactly 1.

        Returns:
        This ComplexNumber, after the normalization
